@Node "Introduzione" "Introduction"
INTRODUCTION:
-------------
MIDI  Filter  is  a Program Change (PC) converter from standard GS/GM format to
your  own  synth  one.   Many MIDI instruments, even they are great (such as my
Roland  JV-80  keyboard or my Yamaha TG-500 expander) do not respect instrument
disposition of GM/GS standard.  

MIDI  Filter is born to help everyone who does not have a GS/GM instrument, but
desires  anyway  to  use  thousands  of  MIDI  bases  which  are present in PD.
@EndNode

@Node "COMELEGGERE" "How To Read This Manual"
HOW TO READ THIS MANUAL:
------------------------
This doc is mainly divided into two parts:  first one describes the use of MIDI
Filter to the user, the second one is a more techy section for the professional
user who desires to know deeply all convertion operations used by MIDI Filter.

@EndNode

@Node "Midi Filter" "Midi Filter"
MIDI FILTER:
------------
Once loaded, MIDI Filter will pop up a window, @{" Main Window " LINK  "Main Window"},
from where you should define main operations.
Keep in mind that, once loaded, MIDI Filter will scan current dir to find these
files:


    * @{"GSNames.Tbl" Link "GSNames.Tbl"} - It is an ASCII table will all 128 names of GS/GM MIDI 
                     instruments. This file is given with MIDI Filter and should 
                     not be modified.

    * @{"Table.Tbl" Link "Table.Tbl"}   - It is a conversion table from GS/GM created with MIDI
                     Filter. It holds all links between GS/GM PC and your
                     synth. The table given with MIDI Filter has been edited
                     to convert files for Roland JV-80.

    * @{"Table.Nms" Link "Table.Nms"}   - It is a table containing all instruments name
                     of your sinth. The one given with MIDI Filter conatins all
                     A and B Banks of a standard Roland JV-80.


Actually, you only NEED the first:  @{"GSNames.Tbl" Link "GSNames.Tbl"}.  
If  you do not have this file, maybe MIDI Filter will not work properely.  Even
if this file is mainly for user reference, many operations may be too difficult
if you do not have @{"GSNames.Tbl" Link "GSNames.Tbl"}.  
@EndNode

@Node "Main Window" "Main Window"
MAIN WINDOW:
------------
From main window, you can choose one of these operations:

    * @{"PC Editor" Link "PC Editor"}   - Program Changes Editor.
    * @{"Names Ed." Link "Names Ed."}   - Instruments Name Editor of your MIDI Synth.
    * @{"About" Link "About"}       - To read an About Message.

But now we have to examin  main window main panel.
It  is  divided into some parts, bigger one contains some infos reguarding MIDI
base  tracks  which  we  are  currently  converting,  track  name, PC value and
corresponding  GS/GM  instrument name.  In the next line we can see MIDI format
used by the file, new PC inserted by MIDI Filter and the name of the instrument
used for the convertion.

In the lower part we find gadget @{"Convert" Link "Convert"} to actually convert a file.

@EndNode

@Node "Convert" "Convert"
CONVERT:
--------
Before  pressing Convert, we should have loaded into memory a MIDI base.  To do
so,  simply  press "Load" gadget.  Once pressed, select by File Request desired
file you wish to convert and press OK.

Now  you  can press "Convert" and the convertion will begin.  Once ended, press
"Save",  select  destination name by File Requester and the converted MIDI file
will be saved where you wish.
@EndNode

@Node "PC Editor" "Program Change Editor"
PC EDITOR:
----------
This  editor  is  mainly divided into two parts:  "Original GS", which contains
original GS instrument names and "New SetUp", which contains names of your MIDI
synthetizer.
Under  "Original GS" and "New SetUp" you should see corresponding PC.  To set a
PC  inside  the  table,  operations  to  do  are  really simple:  select inside
"Original  GS"  the  instrument  you  want to convert.  Then select inside "New
SetUp"  the  new  instrument  which will replace the original one and press the
"OK" gadget between "Original GS" and "New SetUp".

Please, not that, if a convertion table is already present, each time you press
on an instrument inside "Original GS", inside "Name:" you will see the name of
the istrument intended to replace the original one during convertion.

EXAMPLE: "ChrcOrgan" (GS/GM) -->  "PipeOrgan1" (Roland JV-80)

    * Press "ChrcOrgan" inside "Original GS": "Orig.PC" will be 19.
    * Press "PipeOrgan1" inside "New SetUp" : "New.PC"  will be 24.
    * Press "OK"

NOTE: Always press "OK" each time a new instrument is selected for convertion,
or new settings will not be saved.

With "SAVE" gadget you can save convertion table onto disk.

UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFO

From MIDI Filter V1.1 also "Original GS" and "New SetUp" are gadgets. By
pressing them you can load a new name list to change the actual one.

UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFOS --- UPDATE INFO
@EndNode

@Node "Names Ed." "Names Editor"
NAMES ED.:
----------
In this section is posible to memorize your synth names (@{"Table.Nms" Link "Table.Nms"} table).
"Instrument  #"  values change from 0 to 127.  They hold all possible 128 GS/GM
instrument  range.   To memorize a name, you just have to write the name inside
the  string  gadget  (max.   12 chars).  With "Prev" and "Next" gadgets you can
insert/modify  all  names  in  the list.  If you wish to save the list created,
just press "Save" gadget.

@EndNode

@Node "About" "About"
ABOUT:
------
It shows some infos about MIDI Filter. To close the window you just have to
press the "Thanx!" gadget.
@EndNode

@Node "Convert Info" "Convert Infos"
CONVERT INFO:
-------------
MIDI  Filter  works  with  all  MIDI  file  in  memory  to  speed-up  searching
operations.   Parsing  is  done following standard MIDI file format description
and it should completely compatible with future format versions.
Once  selected  the  file,  MIDI Filter will alloc dynamically a memory area to
store  the  file,  then  it  reads the file in RAW mode and store it inside the
allocated  memory area.  From here, with optimized search/replace routines, the
file is converted.

Concectually,  convertion  criteria  is  very simple:  to each GS/GM instrument
*SHOULD* exist one inside your MIDI synth.  Unique correspondance between
GS/GM-->Your Synth is created by the Convertion Table @{"Table.Tbl" Link "Table.Tbl"}.

@EndNode

@Node "GSNames.Tbl" "GSNames.Tbl Table"
GSNAMES.TBL:
------------
It  is  a  very  simple  ASCII  file  of  128  lines  containing  ordered GS/GM
instruments  names.   File  is  fully editable, but names MUST be max 12 chars.
@EndNode

@Node "Table.Tbl" "Table.Tbl Table"
TABLE.TBL:
----------
It is an ASCII file created by @{"PC Editor" Link "PC Editor"}.  
It  holds all new PC values.  You should also modify by hand values inside this
file, but you _*SHOULD*_ know perfectly what you are doing.  We suggest the use
of "PC Editor".

@EndNode

@Node "Table.Nms" "Table.Nms Table"
TABLE.NMS:
----------
It is an ASCII file created by @{"Names Ed." Link "Names Ed."}.
It  holds all instruments name of your Synth.  Names MUST be max 12 chars.  You
can edit it with a text editor.
@EndNode
